Day 6: Semantic HTML (VERY Important 🔥)

Semantic HTML means using meaningful tags that clearly describe the content.

👉 Instead of only using <div>, we use proper tags like:

<header>
<nav>
<main>
<section>
<article>
<footer>

This is VERY important for:

Interviews
SEO (Google ranking)
React component structure
Clean code writing
1. Why Semantic HTML?
Without semantic HTML
<div id="header">Header</div>
<div id="nav">Menu</div>
<div id="content">Content</div>
With semantic HTML
<header>Header</header>
<nav>Menu</nav>
<main>Content</main>

👉 Clean, readable, meaningful

2. Semantic Tags
Header

Used for top section of page

<header>
    <h1>My Website</h1>
</header>
Navigation (nav)

Used for menu links

<nav>
    <a href="#">Home</a>
    <a href="#">About</a>
    <a href="#">Contact</a>
</nav>
Main Content (main)

Primary content of page

<main>
    <h2>Welcome</h2>
    <p>This is main content</p>
</main>
Section (section)

Groups related content

<section>
    <h2>About Me</h2>
    <p>I am a Java Developer</p>
</section>
Article (article)

Independent content (blog, post)

<article>
    <h2>Blog Post</h2>
    <p>This is a blog article</p>
</article>
Aside (aside)

Side content (ads, sidebar)

<aside>
    <p>Advertisement</p>
</aside>
Footer

Bottom section

<footer>
    <p>© 2026 My Website</p>
</footer>
3. Complete Layout Example
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Semantic Page</title>
</head>
<body>

<header>
    <h1>My Portfolio</h1>
</header>

<nav>
    <a href="#">Home</a>
    <a href="#">About</a>
    <a href="#">Projects</a>
    <a href="#">Contact</a>
</nav>

<main>

    <section>
        <h2>About Me</h2>
        <p>I am a Java + React Developer.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Skills</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Java</li>
            <li>Spring Boot</li>
            <li>React</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <article>
        <h2>Latest Project</h2>
        <p>Built a Library Management System using Spring Boot.</p>
    </article>

</main>

<aside>
    <p>Contact me for freelance work!</p>
</aside>

<footer>
    <p>© 2026 Priyadharshini</p>
</footer>

</body>
</html>
4. Difference between <div> and Semantic Tags
<div>	Semantic Tags
Generic container	Meaningful container
No meaning	Gives structure
Hard for SEO	SEO friendly
5. Interview Questions
1. What is semantic HTML?

Answer:

Semantic HTML uses meaningful tags that clearly describe the content, like <header>, <nav>, <section>, and <footer>.

2. Why do we use semantic tags?

Answer:

They improve readability, SEO, accessibility, and help browsers understand the page structure.

3. Difference between <section> and <article>?
section	article
Groups related content	Independent content
Part of page	Can stand alone
4. Why avoid using only <div>?

Answer:

Because <div> has no meaning and makes code harder to understand and less SEO friendly.

5. What is <nav> used for?

Answer:

It is used to define navigation links of the website.
